vs. CHA vs. AC vs. HP</span><hr size=1> I looked at that thread about AC earlier, and there are two things which the poster seems unaware of. It is correct that the min and max damage for a mob is not affected by AC, only the average hit. It is also correct that there is a soft cap beyond which one will have diminishing returns for higher AC. <br>
<br>
However - what is not pointed out is that this soft cap is different for each mob. So for an orc centurion, it may be 180ac, whereas for a sebilite juggernaut it could be 1000ac. In other words, the reason he found an apparent soft cap at around 700ac, is because that is the cap for *the particular mob* he was fighting, nothing more. Against a mob with lower attack it might be 600ac, against a higher attack mob it might be 800ac.<br>
<br>
Also, when looking at a test like this, there is another factor to consider: A 700ac soft cap seems at first glance to be ridiculously low for a krup. And it would be, for a melee class. Because the AC gotten from defense skill has not been thought of, and in this area a warrior would have a good 2-300 more AC than an enchanter. AC from defense skill does not affect how hard you get hit, only your ability to avoid getting hit in the first place, and therefore this can throw off a test that does not take it into account. 700ac for an enchanter is actually a whole heck of a lot of AC gear, whereas a warrior can achieve that more or less naked.<br>
<br>
So really the soft cap at any time is based on 2 factors: First the mob being fought (more specifically it's attack rating), and second your own defense skill. The lower the attack skill of the mob, the lower the cap will be. And the lower your defense skill, the lower the cap will be, as a greater part of your displayed AC comes from equipment than defense skill.<br>
<br>
